India should use clever approaches in making transgenic shift from oil to battery power .
1) for every 50 km outside the cities select &  give an opportunity for a single petrol pump to have one fast charging point.( Not more then one points because technology is changing & more faster charging ports will have adverse effect to change to new upgradation as the initial high investment is already done by multiple points ) selected petrol pumps will jump into a new opportunities as it will establish them ahead into the future against rivals.( If one is unwilling then select the next one . Make them impress with the govt major road sign board showing the power point as a destination all over the city . ) 
In fact it will be the important step to growth as overhead road sign show the way & distance to fast charging point from every direction just like chowks , Hospitals , bus stand , railway station.
2) select Dabas on outskirt of cities to have power point ( first single point on single selected daba, many as demand grow) . One faster charging for atleast one hour & they have a new kind of coustomers at their eatery , taking double profits from fast charging & their regular services  . A first power pointed Daba will establish itself as a prime location for the city.
3) make compulsory ( strictly ) for every car manufacturers to have atleast one entry level alternative battery operated cars in its lineup , like Tata Nexon ( but enty level is more affordable ) which have on par with oil power vehicle with added benifits of  electric power. 
Not those tiny under power but a full fledge & complete package.
 Without the multiple choice public will hesitate into being a first coustomers.
4) don't start as a national mission as all over nation in one go but as a one regional preference. Like Delhi & Mumbai  or metros & planned from inside out for 200 km , well established infrastructure for a metro city will pay the thousand folds head start for tier 2 or 3 cities.
5) reluctant in giving incentives or govt funding to fast charging points. It will have adverse effect on the over all market growth but rather give the opportunity for private market to lead the way ahead. It will start slow but will pace up faster &  sooner then we imagined.
Govt funding will make a good headstart but halt the further growth & after some time fail the overall market penetrations.
6) make a clearcut map to have charging points distributes evenly which spread to a long travel line & not in a clusters into one area ( multiple charging point will happen over time as demand grows but a long chain is very important . 
One single govt office is authorised to do the road map & will be responsible for the delay or miss planning .
7) make sure that a single power point is first placed,  restict making the  multiple point at one place in one go because it will dead lock the further growth & growth or demand is what the industry need. Too many charging point in one area will block the spread of an idea of battery power vehicle a viable option for outside of that area, & even battery vehicles of  that area will reluctant to go out of their areas . 
One single point will deversefied into multiple as the business growth ( rather multiple points in one area will have initial higher cost & newer business growth is unpredictable so a negative growth is seen for few years & then become a profitable. )

I mean, we had the chance to get onto the NEV racetrack earlier, but now China is really very strong on the NEV arena.

Personally...I think this problem is just being thought about and executed backwards...and this also has to do with the way fundamental physics has maintained long standing ideas in entropy and what it actually means for systems.

The problem is the fact that we have localized plants, producing and then having to store and transport energy to other places that are very far away...when the real solution is in the way we create and produce appliances. Entropy is thought of in such a way, where once a system reaches equilibrium, it has used up "all useful energy" but this isn't true. In actuality, the system at equilibrium is operating at a maximally efficient rate.

Therefor what follows, is that appliances should themselves be like little batteries...powered by extremely local energy sources, which then distribute out their surpluses or taking in to cover deficits by other nearby neighbors appliances, until they balance themselves into equilibrium, like a balancing book. Then you no longer need to worry about storage, transportation or centralized hazards. 

Why do we know this is right? Because all life on Earth does this. Do plants have centralized power sources? No...each plant is capable of powering itself...and they distribute what they have in surplus to the rest of the bio-organism...and then eventually to other biomasses which is why we have lifeforms on earth today : Animals get their energy from plants that disperse the energy they receive from the sun. If you think about the Earth as one giant complex system, it's constant parts are taking the suns massive amounts of constant energy, and dispersing it more and more which is how it becomes more complex. If human civilization wishes to advance, fundamental physics, and the way we think about the world has to alter it's perspective away from the paradigm of "more bigger more power." 

Ironically...the atomic bomb...the biggest most destructive weapon ever invented...is a result of the tiniest of tiniest things, little atoms. and I mean, it's this same process that powers the sun too.

The true power of nature, lies in the fact that it's operating at these lower levels at such a massively efficient level, that it dwarfs the lack of efficiency that larger scale organisms like us haven't realized yet, is actually there.

Building electrical generators away from where the power is needed is a waste of money and resources. The cheapest way of producing electricity is with a system of closed loop hydroelectric power stations combined with solar and wind power systems. Closed loop hydroelectric power stations can be built underground or incorporated into building design saving space and placing the power production closer to the point that the power is needed eliminating most substations and transformers. The longer the distance that electricity needs to travel the higher the voltage needs to be. Cities create constant wind currants and all you need is rooftop solar and wind power systems to recharge the closed loop hydroelectric power stations. Unfortunately electrical engineers are obsessed with large scale electrical systems which are not cost effective and are very inefficient. For the same costs as large wind and solar farms that can only power one city, closed loop hydroelectric power stations combined with rooftop wind and solar power systems can power several cities. In Adelaide south Australia the rooftop solar system on houses produce more than 3 times the electricity that can be used by the city and that is just the rooftop solar panels and doesn't include the wind farms, coal power stations and solar farms that produce more than 20 times the amount of power that is used during the day, the government spent millions on batteries that are very expensive and only have a maximum lifespan of 10 years. For the same price as the batteries they could have built a system of closed loop hydroelectric power stations strategically placed throughout the city that with proper maintenance last over 100 years. Closed loop hydroelectric power stations are very cheap batteries that only need water and gravity to store the electricity from solar and wind power systems. A closed loop hydroelectric power station is basically 2 water tanks a few turbines and generators and pumps, because they can be built by local companies the cost of manufacturing, matenance and transport are a lot cheaper than the large wind turbines that are commonly used. Electricity is very easy to produce and store but not using the old fashioned method of large scale electricity production in remote areas.

I just read a story about a man who blew up his Tesla because he didn't want to pay $23,000 to replace his batteries. I hear from people like this CEO that electric vehicles are the obliviously superior economic choice, because of lower maintenance costs, but corporations aren't going to sell us less of something. They're not going sell us a car that will last a long time and be cheap to operate and maintain. There's no profit in that. They're going to find a way to make electric vehicles at least as profitable as ICE vehicles, whether it be through expensive batteries or subscription services or tying consumers into a certain software ecosystem, etc. Whatever it is, there is no way EVs can be more economical for consumers than ICE vehicles because corporations can't tolerate a loss of profits. Even if EVs replace ICE vehicles, and they very well might, they will not be less expensive for consumers because that's not how corporations make profits.

Quick swap configuration has some compelling advantages that should be considered. First, with a family of standardized models with respect to size and shape as well as electrical connectivity, a degree of protection from technological obsolescence as breakthrough innovations in storage density and durability comes forth is provided. A market for EV‚Äôs for dwellers in high density multifamily urban and suburban areas where huge charging parts, with corn rows of charging poles are out of the question. With regional charging and checkout distribution centers located adjacent to power generating plants and renewable energy harvesting fields, the risk of overload of neighborhood distribution grids by homeowner charging setups is greatly reduced. Quick swap stations as replacement for fueling stations would obviate range anxiety for long distance travel, as well as lost usage driving time for company fleets. The elimination of inherently empty back hauls by tank wagons with 18-wheelers would be a strong environmental plus! The customer would no longer own the power packs. If the green car was cheaper than the gasoline car, and drivers replaced at the same rate as today (100M/yr), we could convert the existing fleet (2.5B total) in 25 years without asking drivers to spend more money, which they would probably accept.
To beat gas, we can explore cheap green liquid ammonia that powers fuel cells, which produces electricity, which turns motors, which turns wheels. And we can also explore standardized swappable low-range cheap plug-in EV batteries that use fewer rare earth materials.
Liquid ammonia has three big challenges: (a) it consumes three times more volume relative to gasoline per unit energy, (b) it needs to be chilled to -32¬∞C, and (c) ammonia vapor needs to be kept out of noses. To maintain refrigeration, ammonia-based vehicles would need to maintain constant communication with a central authority, and if refrigeration failed, a service vehicle would need to visit to either repair or remove ammonia. A plug-in swappable standard refrigeration hardware unit used by all vehicles might make automated replacement easier. A refrigeration maintenance system would ultimately add to the total cost of ownership. 
The good news is that liquid ammonia fuel made with Generation 4 should be cheaper than gasoline, per unit energy. And a fuel cell's 50% efficiency is better than an internal combustion engine's 25% efficiency. Also, one can explore combusting hydrogen, as explained in this video. In summary, if engineers can get the total cost of ownership for an ammonia-based car to be less than a gasoline-based car, it might be viable.
Currently, proprietary batteries are installed in each EV car and are periodically charged. Alternatively, one could have a standard plug-in battery, where all cars use the same form, and are swapped with a fresh battery in less than 60 seconds. Car owners would pay for the energy consumed and wear on the battery. Cavities would be dug out at key locations and a mechanism would be dropped in via crane that implements charging, storage and swap. Cars would position themselves over the mechanism, and the swap would occur automatically. Swap mechanisms might be positioned next to highway on/off ramps, and next to frequented establishments. For example, the corner next to your local drug store might be convenient. If swap is easy and fast, then shorter range batteries would become more acceptable; and these tend to be cheaper and use fewer rare earth materials.
Installing swap chambers or liquid ammonia refueling infrastructure would be an enormous undertaking. 
Currently, gov't observes that EV battery prices have dropped over the past few years, extrapolates forward, and declares this as the transportation decarbonization plan. However, this might not work due to rare earth constraints. Subsequently, we should consider investing heavily in transportation that is cheaper than gas and is not resource constrained. For example, gov't could invest $10M/yr over 3 years for each of the following R&D initiatives:
‚Ä¢	Design swappable plug-in battery infrastructure. 
‚Ä¢	Design ammonia-based car.
‚Ä¢	Design an automated ammonia refueling station.
‚Ä¢	Design a standardized plug-in ammonia refrigeration unit & tank.
‚Ä¢	Design an automated city-wide ammonia refrigeration monitoring and maintenance system.
In summary, engineers need to figure out how to build 2,500,000 cheap green cars over ~25 years.

Battery swapping is a terrible, terrible idea. There's a reason why Tesla never followed through on it. On most EVs, the battery is the single largest, heaviest, most expensive, most dangerous component. It should be sealed tight, rigidly fixed in place, shielded, and protected as much as possible from the external environment to reduce the chance of puncture or other damage.

Battery swapping requires quick and easy access through the bottom of the car. This is a TERRIBLE idea because it creates so many opportunities for the battery to be scratched, scraped, dinged, dropped. The bolts, screws, guide rails and all other parts on the undercarriage will also be exposed to wear and tear over time as well as potential damage from a careless battery swap. Perhaps a small part that holds the battery in place is now slightly bent but not enough for anyone to notice until it's too late. It won't be long before we see news stories about car batteries that just *plop* fall out of the car on the highway or in city traffic after hitting a pothole. I can already picture a battery falling out of a speeding car, scraping the ground, sparks flying, flipping end over end, suffering even more damage from the multi-car pileup, and finally bursting into flames. This is a disaster waiting to happen. 

There's also the issue of quality control. When you're constantly swapping in a different battery, you have no idea how old it is, nor how it's been handled (or mishandled) in the past. Was it always stored and charged properly? Was it previously damaged but not severely enough to be sent back to the manufacturer and instead shoved back into inventory? The more battery swapping is scaled up, the more the quality control issues will pile up. The problems will grow exponentially.

No data on how many cars per hour they can handle. If the batteries are slow charged, they might pretty quickly run out of full batteries. No data on how many modules they keep at a swap station. No data on how much range the car has running on a swapped battery. No data on whether the swappable battery can be fast charged while in the car. In other words, a useless puff piece.
And leaving aside those tech issues, I have serious doubts about the financial viability. Batteries are very expensive. At the scale they are working at, they have to be spending somewhere around $200 per kWh at the module level. That's $10,000 worth of batteries for each 50 kWh swap. If you assume 4 cars per hour, and a charge time of 8 hours before you can re-deploy a battery, you need 32 cars worth of batteries, $320,000. At 10 cents per mile, that implies a swap will cost about $20 to the driver. The power in the battery will cost the swap station at least $10. Leaving aside all the other costs of running the station, at $10 profit per swap, They will need 1000 swaps just to pay for the battery.

Good idea but a few points to ponder
1.  Do we have Lithium or cobalt for batteries for these Electric vehicles.. We import them ...right. And can we compete with China  LI-ion battery manufacturing with their huge reserves of Lithium and presently leading the World production and export of Li-ion batteries
2.  What about the generation of electricity to charge these batteries? We are using coal, which defeats the entire purpose. Going electric in the vehicle segment but using polluting fossil fuels to produce the electricity to charge so many EVs is overall counterproductive.
3. That brings us to cleaner energy production. So thinking of Nuclear plants. Only 3% of our electricity need is met by our 21 functional Nuclear power plants. Reasons are import dependency for fuel grade Uranium. We have reserves of Thorium-rich Monazite. But Thorium can not be used in a reactor directly for power production. It has to undergo an expensive nuclear treatment to convert it into Uranium-233 a radioactive isotope. Is it clean ?... Well not exactly. Security risks and toxic residues like U-232 (half life -1,60,000 years), Technetium-99 (half life 300,000 years) and Iodine-129 (half life of 15.7 million years) are definitely not good for you when it will seeps in to your water table however deep you hide it.
4. What are we left with...Solar and wind...With the existing technology the scales required can not be met.
5.  Alternative methods like Batteries which do not need recharge? Like Hydrogen fuel cell? Well it is efficient, it is zero emission, byproducts are just heat and water which is not toxic(used by astronauts as drinking water....yes Im not joking) and its the most abundant element on earth. But cons are(a)  hydrogen extraction requires energy....(b) some metals used are Platinum(costlier than gold)  (c)  highly combustible and risk of 350 Volts electric shock////Yiiikes.
6.  Dont hold your breath but alternative battery chemistry with very high energy density and none of the cons listed above may be the answer if rapid adoption and end-use case is needed.
7.  Last but not least...where are we going to dump so many IC engines.
8. Not to sound discouraging but just a different perspective. Energy production has to be environmentally clean...and our lifestyle must change  to reduce carbon footprint....no two ways about that ....but will technology help and how much time will it take? So as Akshat clearly warned you in the beginning...Invest but not all your eggs in one basket...Thanks

Great explanation Akshat! However, I'm still doubtful about going all-in on this market because I have a hunch that the growth is overestimated. I'll explain my logic, please correct me if I'm wrong.

Unlike other sectors, EV is set to REPLACE the existing IC engine automobiles and not CREATE a new buyer segment. If I have an IC-based car today, I would never go and buy an EV on top of it. Instead of creating a new blue ocean market altogether, it's going to share the pie with the existing automobiles sales market. So IC-based automobile sales will decrease and EV sales will increase. In the coming years, doesn't this translate to all OEMs adjusting their portfolio of manufactured vehicle parts? They will reduce IC-based parts and increase EV parts in their portfolio. For the OEMs, the revenue from IC parts will reduce, EV parts will increase, and balance out each other. So when we see the EV sales numbers, %growth will be through the roof, but the actual ROI on vehicle manufacturer stock investments in India will still see only slightly accelerated growth. To sum up, there is definitely growth potential in the EV market, but maybe it's being overestimated. The assumption being, EV is not a new market like the world perceives it. It's a replacement for an existing one. Investing in companies such as Tesla would give massive returns, but the OEMs, maybe not as much.

Because the average motor vehicle in the US is about 12 yo this year, up from 11+ yo in 2020, the average citizen may fairly quickly figure out that if they don't buy a BEV for their next vehicle that a substantial investment in an ICE vehicle anytime starting now will be worth next to nothing by the time they sell or trade-in to buy another one in the future. Combined with the impact on OEMs experiencing the demand for ICE plummeting, this could drive a switchover in many if not most markets. As BEV‚Äôs grow in market share more variations will show up in the marketplace. This will help drive adoption. As adoption of BEVs rises the supporting infrastructure for ICE vehicles will deteriorate. New filling stations will not be added due to flagging needs and because additional cost for expensive fuel holding tanks will add to that equation. I expect a tipping point will be reached where finding expensive petrol/gasoline/diesel and BEV adoption will quickly flip to 99% of new cars. Just a few specialized ICE vehicles continue for another decade or two.The adoption of BEVs will further be supported by the increased governmental investment in sustainable energy infrastructure. However‚Ä¶there is vast investment in old technology that will mitigate the changeover. Most of that is aging and has an increased cost to maintain. But taking all that into consideration makes it difficult to set time lines. It seems to be happening increasingly quickly though and much of the world is looking to see it happen between 2030 and 2050. That seems about right. New vehicles flip to 90-95% BEV by 2030 worldwide and that would be a vast improvement to our environment. 2025-2026 BEV production should reach 5-10 million units worldwide and the flip should begin shortly afterward.

PSU insurers offer car insurance in least premium and have best claim settlement. They usually charge almost 40-50% less than getting insurance from dealers. 
Claim settlement ratio is a vague concept to measure efficiency of an insurance company. You should instead focus on amount of claim settlement by companies. Pvt cos are known for settling small claim very swiftly and are notorious for denying (on any flimsy grounds) or under-settling big claims. So they can easily maintain good claim settlement ratio despite having far lesser amount settlement ratio.
PSUs have backing of govt and claim settlement is transparent and generous irrespective of the claim amount. They simple reason is: they have to strictly follow IRDAI guidelines and PSUs have social service as priority not brute profits. And now a days they match or even exceed the TAT( turn around time) compared to PVT companies. If you check the no of complaints against insurers in website of Ombudsman, Beema lokpal or IRDAI, private companies top the disgraceful list and govt companies are least tarnished.
Now,the question arises why dealers or online portals / web aggregators don't prefer PSUs
1) Huge commission paid by Pvt cos to dealers and online web aggregators. So, they sideline PSU insurers and charge hefty premiums from unsuspecting customers so that they can enjoy mammoth share of your premium as commission, totally flouting IRDAI rules.
2) The dealers and web aggregators have to scrupulously comply with IRDAI guidelines while dealing with PSU insurers which will reduce any foul play or   unfair practices which are meant for safeguarding customers against any fraud. Remember,if your claim is stuck by dealer or Pvt cos,you are nowhere to go but in govt companies, strict compliance saves any injustice. So dealers want monopoly in their hands not yours.
Thus, you can draw the inference as to why PSU insurers should the only choice while buying insurance for your loved vehicle.
The 4 renowned PSU/ Govt insurance companies are
1) UNITED INDIA INSURANCE CO. LTD
2) NEW INDIA ASSURANCE CO. LTD.
3) NATIONAL INSURANCE CO. LTD.
4) ORIENTAL INSURANCE CO. LTD.
So, next time you buy a new vehicle,never purchase insurance from dealer instead approach PSU office and get cover for your vehicle. And whenever you renew your cover, do the same .

One very important point is missed.
I strongly feel we should NOT buy Personal accident insurance cover alongwith the Motor insurance policy.
1. The accident insurance cover is only applicable for the owner of the vehicle. So if any of your family member meets accident with your vehicle they would get nothing in cover.
2. Limit is only 15 Lakhs.
3. it will only cover accidental damage while driving that insured vehicle only.

So its far better that you buy a separate Personal accidental insurance cover as
1. It will cover accident due to any reason not just while riding the vehicle.
2. Cover will be far bigger amount.
3. You can take floater plan with your family members.

Hi Akshat,

Masala bonds are essentially a debt instrument but relatively more secure. It does have the disadvantages of currency fluctuations associated with it but there are also some tax benefits associated with currency appreciation, if that happens.

Masala Bonds, like a spicy Indian dish, are a financial concoction with a unique twist. Introduced in India by the International Finance Corporation in 2014, these bonds allow Indian entities to raise money abroad, but here's the kicker: they're denominated in Indian rupees, not the local currency. So, if the rupee takes a nosedive, it's the investor who gets the spicy surprise!

These bonds are like a Bollywood drama, featuring both government and private entities. Foreign investors outside India can partake, as long as they're from countries that play by financial rules. The benefits? High-interest rates, a boost of confidence in the Indian economy, and even tax exemptions on capital gains in rupees.

But, beware! The proceeds can't be used for everything ‚Äì no real estate splurges or risky equity investments. So, while Masala Bonds add some flavor to finance, they come with their own set of rules and spice levels.

Masala bonds are a way for Indian companies and organizations to borrow money from people and institutions outside of India. What makes them special is that these bonds are written in Indian Rupees but can be bought and sold in foreign currencies, like the US dollar or the euro.

Here's why they're useful:

1. More Money Sources: Indian companies can use masala bonds to get money from international investors, not just within India. It's like getting money from people all around the world.

2. Less Money Risk: Since masala bonds are in Indian Rupees, Indian companies don't have to worry about the value of other currencies going up and down. This makes it safer for them to borrow money internationally.

3. Global Investments: People from other countries can invest in India without dealing with Indian Rupees directly. They can invest in these bonds and get a slice of the Indian economy.

4. Boosting the Rupee: Masala bonds help make the Indian Rupee more important in international money dealings, kind of like how the US dollar is used worldwide.

5. Building Things: The money raised from masala bonds is often used to build important things in India, like new energy projects or roads.

6. More Choices for Investors: For investors, it's a way to spread their money around and not have all their investments in one place.

However, there are some risks, like changes in exchange rates or the possibility that the company might not pay back the money. So, while masala bonds can be very useful, they're not without risks, and both the companies and the people investing in these bonds need to be careful.

Youngsters starting in investing need to learn the ropes, know how much risk they can handle and spread their investments around. Some folks get help from money experts or do their homework before making investment moves. It's all about being smart with your money.

Masala bonds are rupee-denominated bonds issued outside of India, primarily in international financial markets. Their utility lies in:

Diversification: They allow Indian entities to raise capital from global investors, reducing dependence on domestic sources.

Currency Risk Mitigation: Issuing in rupees can help Indian issuers avoid currency risk, as they don't have to convert the funds into foreign currency.

Access to Global Markets: Provides access to a wider pool of international investors and a broader capital base.

Attracting Foreign Investment: Attracts foreign investors to India's debt market, fostering economic growth.

Financial Inclusion: Can promote inclusion by bringing in a more diverse set of investors into the Indian financial system.

Interest Rate Arbitrage: May provide cost-effective financing compared to domestic interest rates.

Overall, masala bonds facilitate capital raising and investment, helping Indian entities expand and access international markets.

Hi,
Masala Bonds are rupee-denominated.
Indian entities or companies issue these outside India to raise money. The issue of these bonds is in Indian currency rather than local currency. 
Thus, if the rupee rate falls, the investor will bear the loss and If the rupee appreciates at the time of maturity, it benefits the investor.

Masala Bonds are debt instruments used to raise money from foreign investors in local currency. These are rupee-denominated bonds issued outside India by an Indian entity. The framework for the issuance of rupee bonds overseas falls within the External Commercial Borrowings policy.

A masala bond, also known as a rupee-denominated bond, is a financial instrument issued outside of India but denominated in Indian rupees. The term "masala" refers to the spiciness of Indian cuisine and is used metaphorically to imply the Indian flavor of these bonds. Masala bonds allow Indian entities to raise funds from international investors, thereby accessing a wider pool of capital.

Masala bonds are typically issued by corporations, financial institutions, or international organizations seeking to finance infrastructure projects, corporate expansion, or other investment opportunities in India. These bonds are settled in Indian rupees, which means that the issuer bears the exchange rate risk, unlike dollar-denominated bonds where investors bear the risk.

The introduction of masala bonds in 2015 by the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) was part of a broader effort to attract foreign investment and deepen the Indian capital market. They provide an alternative fundraising avenue for Indian entities, particularly those involved in sectors like infrastructure and manufacturing.

Investing in masala bonds can be attractive for international investors as it allows them to gain exposure to Indian markets and diversify their portfolio. However, they also come with risks, including currency exchange rate fluctuations and the creditworthiness of the issuing entity.

Masala bonds have contributed to the growth of India's bond market and have been well-received by investors. They offer an innovative financing option, promote internationalization of the Indian rupee, and facilitate capital flows into the country.

2. For foreign entities, issuing bonds denominated in Indian rupees can help them manage currency risks. By issuing bonds in rupees, they can avoid the currency risk associated with borrowing in a foreign currency and then converting it back to their home currency.
3. Masala bonds typically offer higher yields compared to other debt instruments, providing Indian investors with an opportunity to earn higher returns on their investments.
4. Masala bonds can provide a boost to the Indian economy by attracting foreign capital and encouraging foreign entities to invest in the country. This can also help strengthen the Indian rupee by increasing demand for the currency.

Overall, Masala bonds are a useful financial instrument that can provide benefits to both foreign entities and Indian investors.

Masala bonds are a useful tool for Indian companies looking to raise funds from global investors, manage currency risk, and develop the domestic bond market. They also help to promote the internationalization of the Indian rupee.

Masala bonds is a win-win sittuation for the borrower, lender and for the country as a whole.

Borrower: Can tap the international funds at a cheaper interest rate without worrying the rupee depreciation.

Lender: Lender will get an opportunity to diversify their investment and get the higher rate of return when compared to their local interest rates.

Country(India): Rupee would be intenationalised which leads to strengthening the rupee and its stability agains foreign currencies.

Masala Bonds are rupee-denominated bonds issued outside India by Indian entities. They are debt instruments which help to raise money in local currency from foreign investors. This moves the exchange rate risk from the bond issuer to the investor.
Lets say reliance wants to issue bonds in the US. If it issues in USD, then the payment that reliance has to make to investors will fluctuate based on USD/INR, thereby exposing reliance to exchange rate risk. However, if reliance issues masala bonds, then these bonds will be denominated in INR and payments made by reliance to investors will be in INR. Now, the risk exposure of reliance has reduced and the investor is exposed to exchange rate risk.
